{"title":"What's 'up' with vision-language models? Investigating their struggle with spatial reasoning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing VL benchmarks confound spatial reasoning with other skills and real-world priors, making it unclear whether models truly understand basic relations like left/right, on/under, in front of/behind.","method":"Introduce three tightly controlled benchmarks where only the spatial preposition varies between caption options: What'sUp (820 real photos in 205 sets controlling lighting/background; each set includes on/under/left/right for the same object pair, enabling pair- and set-wise consistency metrics), COCO-spatial, and GQA-spatial (curated to isolate mutually exclusive prepositions). Evaluate 18 VL models by selecting the correct caption among options that differ only by preposition. All models perform poorly vs. humans (e.g., BLIP-VQA averages ~56% vs. human ~99%), revealing systematic failures in basic spatial reasoning."},{"problem":"Why do pre-trained VL models struggle to learn spatial relations despite strong performance on other tasks?","method":"Analyze LAION-2B (used for CLIP-style pretraining) and find spatial prepositions are extremely rare (<0.22% after denoising), often ambiguous (e.g., frame-of-reference issues), and seldom required by the contrastive objective, limiting learnable signal. Complement with a representation probe using visual analogies on What'sUp: CLIP embeddings show ~9% analogy accuracy for prepositions versus ~61% for colors (and 100% direct color classification), indicating weak linear structure for spatial relations in learned image features. Together, these diagnoses point to insufficient and noisy supervision for spatial relations during pretraining and objectives that do not incentivize learning them."},{"problem":"Can simple modeling or data interventions recover spatial reasoning in current VL models?","method":"Test three data-informed interventions: (a) re-normalize image–text scores by caption priors computed on external image sets; yields small/inconsistent gains across datasets. (b) Replace the rare word 'behind' with frequent LAION token 'in the background'; CLIP accuracy on the relevant subset jumps from ~52% to ~67%, suggesting latent but poorly surfaced spatial knowledge. (c) Finetune CLIP on COCO/GQA-spatial, a LAION subset rich in prepositions, and with hard-negative captions made by preposition swaps; results show limited or distribution-specific gains (COCO/GQA up, What'sUp down) and inability to fit hard negatives (very high train loss), indicating naive finetuning and prompting are insufficient without stronger inductive biases or denser supervision."}]}
